 I never see her no more. And I put in - when - I had a cable come out there, saying that mother was taken ill, and when I got up and see me old Commanding Officer I said to him, look, I says, just had this letter, I said, from Portland, home. My mother i
s
 seriously ill. Can I have compassionate leave to go home? So he said, well, he said, you'll have to verify this. Have to verify it. I said, right, I said, what have we got to do? Well, he said, you've got to send a cable to your home to the police and as
k
 them to go and verify the illness, which I did. And - when the message came back the policeman said life extinct. I went to the Co.O. when I got the letter, I said there you are sir, he said, I'm sorry son you can't go now. I couldn't come then. About fi
v
e months afterwards I got leave to come home. And that's through my damned silly sister. Because when the police went to the house and said - I've had a message from your brother or from Sergeant so and so to know - the illness. So she said, mother just p
assed away. I could have killed the bitch. You see, once this here policeman took that down of course they said, life extinct. So I was beat. I said I wouldn't do no more soldiering. I went back to war then, kill the Germans. That was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10236034\charrsid2572417 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2583594\charrsid2572417 y
